`Array.prototype.every.call(arrayLike, fun)` is a way to do `arrayLike.every(fun)` for something that's not an array, just array-like. The array methods are written in a way that most of them will work on any array-like if you want. Doing `arr.every(fun)` would internally do the same (actually calling a method uses the same internal structure as `apply`, not `call`, which takes arguments stored in an array-like, not a parameter list with all separate, but is otherwise the same)

`item => !item.checked` is almost same as function expression `function(item) { return !item.checked; }`, it's a more compact notation introduced in ECMAScript 2015.

